---
description: Utils file structure pattern
alwaysApply: true
---

When creating utils files, follow this pattern:

1. Export individual functions, classes, and interfaces as named exports
2. At the end of the file, export a utils object (named after the module) that contains all functions/classes as a const object
3. Types and interfaces remain as separate exports (not included in the utils object)

This pattern allows both individual imports and namespace imports:

```typescript
// Individual imports
import { functionName } from "./utils";

// Namespace imports
import { UtilsName } from "./utils";
UtilsName.functionName();
```

Example:

```typescript
export function helperFunction() {
  // ...
}

export function anotherHelper() {
  // ...
}

export const UtilsName = {
  helperFunction,
  anotherHelper,
} as const;
```

For files with classes instead of functions, include the classes in the utils object:

```typescript
export class MyClass {
  // ...
}

export const UtilsName = {
  MyClass,
} as const;
```

